The example below (and variations of it) isn't possible in Hugo:

```handlebars
{{ $r := resources.FromString "foo.css" "body { color: blue; }" }}
{{/* How do I get $r to resolve as an import in main.css?  */}}
{{ $css := resources.Get "css/main.css" | css.Build }}
```

And in `assets/css/main.js`:

```css
@import "foo.css" screen;
@import "bar.css" print;
```

The example above uses `css.Build`, but this is also relevant for (at least) `css.Sass`, `js.Build` and `js.Batch`. There are more or less ugly workardounds for the above (e.g. `resources.Concat` or passing in css vars in a map), but it would be nice to have a direct way that worked for all (I have a new proposal in mind that would need this).

I suggest we add [importContext](https://gohugo.io/functions/js/batch/#import-contex) to [resources.Copy](https://gohugo.io/functions/resources/copy/#article) and make the logic that's currently implemented in [js.Batch](https://gohugo.io/functions/js/batch/#article) also work for the other relevant funcs, e.g:

```handlebars
{{ $foo := resources.FromString "foo.css" "body { color: blue; }" }}
{{ $bar := resources.FromString "bar.css" "body { color: green; }" }}
{{ $main := resources.Get "css/main.css" | resources.Copy (dict "importContext" (slice $foo $bar)) }}
{{ $css := $main | css.Build }}
```

The current signature of `resources.Copy` is:

```
resources.Copy TARGETPATH RESOURCE
```

I suggest we 

```
resources.Copy [STRING or MAP] RESOURCE
```

And make it optional (we can determine a path from RESOURCE). So for the MAP options it would look like:


```handlebars
{{ $opts := dict
   "targetPath" "foo.css"
   "importContext" (slice $foo $bar)
}}
```

In the above `importContext` is the same as described in [inputContext](https://gohugo.io/functions/js/batch/#import-context) -- which also allows constructs ala:

```handlebars
{{ $common := resources.Match "/js/headlessui/*.*" }}
{{ $importContext := (slice $.Page ($common.Mount "/js/headlessui" ".")) }}
{{ $opts := dict
   "importContext" $importContext
}}
```

This is a formal proposal to add bibliography support to Pandoc content. Over the years we have had 4 pull requests[^1] (without corresponding proposals) to implement this capability, a powerful and well-designed Pandoc feature.

The **only** change will be to add the `--citeproc` flag to the `pandoc` command.

- There is no longer a need to check for `--citeproc` support. This flag has been available since Pandoc v2.11, released over 5 years ago on 11 Oct 2020. In 2026, anyone who is not using v2.11 or later should be.
- We will not add any configuration settings such as allowing arbitrary CLI flags.
- We will not add any dedicated front matter fields: bibliography file path, citation style, inline  reference definition, and other settings are controlled by a metadata block within the content file.

Regarding bibliography files and citation style files:
- These must exist on the local file system; they cannot be imported from modules.
- Pandoc can read these files from outside of the project directory. We could add the `--sandbox` CLI flag to prevent this, but I have no idea how many existing projects use  `!include` directives that reference files outside of the current working directory, so this would be a breaking change. I think in the past we've looked at things like this, but assert that if someone adds `pandoc` to the exec allowlist they are aware of the implications.


I've tried this myself, and it works very well within a Hugo context. Other than the metadata block, the only thing you need to add is something like this to your CSS:

```css
.csl-entry {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start; 
    margin-bottom: 0.5em;    
}

.csl-left-margin {
    flex-shrink: 0;       
    width: 2.5em;           
    text-align: left;      
}

.csl-right-inline {
    flex-grow: 1;          
    padding-left: 0.5em;  
}
```



[^1]: #4800, #7529, #8610, #9953.
